# Canonical Integrity License v1.0

Copyright (c) 2026 Kai Stefan Dietrich

Repository: Integrity Nexus

---

## 1. Purpose

This license is intended to preserve the integrity of the canonical research architecture while allowing public reading, citation, sharing, and independent further development.

The goal is:

```text
Share: yes.
Cite: yes.
Study: yes.
Build upon independently: yes.
Modify the canonical material: no.
Misrepresent modified material as canonical Integrity Nexus: no.
```

---

## 2. Canonical Work

The canonical work is the Integrity Nexus repository authored by Kai Stefan Dietrich.

The canonical repository is maintained at:

```text
https://github.com/integrity-nexus-kai/Integrity_Nexus
```

Only author-approved changes in the canonical repository are considered canonical Integrity Nexus material.

---

## 3. Permitted Uses

You may:

- read and study the material,
- cite the material,
- link to the canonical repository,
- share unchanged copies with attribution,
- discuss, review, criticize, or audit the material,
- build independent work inspired by the material,
- create independent implementations, tools, or research programs that reference the material.

---

## 4. Attribution Requirement

Any public use, citation, review, or reference should identify:

```text
Kai Stefan Dietrich
Integrity Nexus
https://github.com/integrity-nexus-kai/Integrity_Nexus
```

Do not imply endorsement, co-authorship, approval, peer review, or institutional validation unless explicitly granted in writing.

---

## 5. Modification Restriction

You may not publish, redistribute, or present modified versions of the canonical Integrity Nexus documents, structure, governance model, object model, or research architecture as if they were the original or canonical Integrity Nexus material.

Modified versions must not use the name "Integrity Nexus" in a way that suggests canonical status, author approval, or continuity with the original repository.

---

## 6. Independent Further Development

Independent further development is allowed when it is clearly marked as independent and non-canonical.

Independent derivative projects must:

- use a clearly distinct project name,
- state that they are not the canonical Integrity Nexus repository,
- identify any inspiration or reference to Integrity Nexus with attribution,
- avoid implying author approval or official continuation,
- avoid modifying and redistributing canonical Integrity Nexus materials as canonical material.

---

## 7. Forks and Mirrors

Public mirrors or forks are permitted only when they preserve the canonical material unchanged or clearly identify all changes as non-canonical.

A fork, mirror, or derivative repository must not present itself as the canonical Integrity Nexus repository unless explicitly authorized by Kai Stefan Dietrich.

---

## 8. Tools and Scripts

Tools and scripts included in this repository are part of the canonical repository material unless a separate license is provided for a specific file or directory.

Using a tool for private or internal analysis is allowed.

Redistributing modified tool code as canonical Integrity Nexus tooling is not allowed without author approval.

---

